1
00:01:38,665 --> 00:01:40,189
<i>[Woman]</i>
<i>*Every night and day *</i>

2
00:01:40,266 --> 00:01:42,757
- [Bell Ringing]
<i>- *And I never lost one minute of sleepin'*</i>

3
00:01:42,836 --> 00:01:45,771
<i>* Worryin' 'bout the way</i>
<i>things might have been *</i>

4
00:01:45,839 --> 00:01:48,967
<i>*Big wheel keep on turnin'*</i>

5
00:01:49,042 --> 00:01:52,978
[Chattering]
<i>*Proud Mary keep on burnin'*</i>

6
00:01:53,046 --> 00:01:55,844
<i>*</i> Rollin', rollin' <i>*</i>

7
00:01:55,915 --> 00:01:58,440
<i>*</i> Rollin' on a river <i>*</i>

8
00:01:58,518 --> 00:02:02,113
<i>*</i> Cleaned a lot of plates in Memphis <i>*</i>

9
00:02:02,188 --> 00:02:04,782
<i>*Pumped a lot of'tane</i>
<i>in New Orleans *</i>

10
00:02:04,858 --> 00:02:06,689
<i>[Dice Rattling]</i>
Coming out, folks.

11
00:02:06,759 --> 00:02:09,353
Place your bets.
Place your bets.

12
00:02:10,897 --> 00:02:14,094
[Yells]
I can't lose tonight!

13
00:02:14,167 --> 00:02:18,160
Don't say that.
It brings bad luck.
I do not believe in luck.

14
00:02:18,238 --> 00:02:20,536
<i>*Rollin</i>; <i>rollin'*</i>

15
00:02:20,607 --> 00:02:22,541
<i>*Rollin'on a river *</i>

16
00:02:22,609 --> 00:02:25,009
Okay, Lonnie,
he's winning big.
It's now or never.

17
00:02:33,553 --> 00:02:36,317
I think it's goin' down.
Wilson just sent Lonnie
to the elevator.

18
00:02:36,389 --> 00:02:39,483
Loud and clear, Lieutenant.
If she's comin', I have a front-row seat.

19
00:02:48,468 --> 00:02:53,064
I've got her.
She just went into Acton's suite.

20
00:02:53,139 --> 00:02:55,801
<i>*Rollin</i>; <i>rollin'**</i>

21
00:02:55,875 --> 00:02:58,036
Muntzy, be careful.

22
00:02:58,111 --> 00:03:00,671
[Over Earpiece]
Hey, hey. I got 10 years on you, buddy.

23
00:03:00,747 --> 00:03:03,011
I'm the original man of steel.

24
00:03:03,082 --> 00:03:05,676
You're the one I'm worried about.
You're in that bed of snakes.

25
00:03:29,509 --> 00:03:32,478
[Lonnie On Earpiece]
Wilson, I'm finished.

26
00:03:32,545 --> 00:03:34,536
Well, be sure nobody sees you.

27
00:03:34,614 --> 00:03:36,946
There's no one in the hallway
but an electrician.

28
00:03:37,016 --> 00:03:40,042
Electrician? You didn't say anything
about an electrician.

29
00:03:40,119 --> 00:03:42,110
He works for the hotel.
I've seen him around.

30
00:03:42,188 --> 00:03:45,555
- Stay in the room.
- Croupier, for you.

31
00:03:45,625 --> 00:03:47,616
Wilson.

32
00:03:47,694 --> 00:03:50,595
<i>**[Woman Singing, Indistinct]</i>

33
00:03:50,663 --> 00:03:52,961
We are calling it a night.

34
00:03:53,032 --> 00:03:55,398
<i>Come on, sweetheart. Let's go.</i>

35
00:03:55,468 --> 00:03:58,164
Make sure security is behind us
until we get these in the room safe.

36
00:03:58,238 --> 00:03:59,728
- All right?
- All right.

37
00:04:02,375 --> 00:04:04,366
Delay him.

38
00:04:06,879 --> 00:04:11,111
I want you to stay close to Mr. Acton.
He's carrying a great deal of cash.
<i>Right.</i>

39
00:04:12,719 --> 00:04:15,415
Lonnie, get out of the room fast.

40
00:04:15,488 --> 00:04:18,321
Acton's on his way up.
What about the guy on the ladder?

41
00:04:18,391 --> 00:04:22,259
If he follows you, I'll handle him.
You get in your car
and head east out of town.

42
00:04:22,328 --> 00:04:24,296
We'll pick up the film from you there.

43
00:04:30,837 --> 00:04:32,828
She's leaving in a hurry, Lieutenant.

44
00:04:32,905 --> 00:04:36,500
I know. Wilson just put me in charge.
We've got a broken play.
Can you follow Lonnie?

45
00:04:36,576 --> 00:04:38,544
Back me up if I blow it.

46
00:04:38,611 --> 00:04:41,307
We've got six months
in this one, Muntzy.
I'll be right behind you.

47
00:04:41,381 --> 00:04:45,112
Charles, security can only do so much
in a crowd with you carrying
all these chips.

48
00:04:45,184 --> 00:04:48,517
I'd feel a lot better
if we took it to the cashier.
No, I don't wanna...

49
00:04:48,588 --> 00:04:51,853
- That's good advice, Mr. Acton.
I'd recommend it.
- You're probably right.

50
00:04:51,924 --> 00:04:54,119
<i>They're clumsy as hell anyway.</i>

51
00:04:55,228 --> 00:05:00,530
<i>*But it's time you got the news *</i>

52
00:05:01,534 --> 00:05:04,264
<i>*I'm gonna harden my heart *</i>

53
00:05:04,337 --> 00:05:06,532
<i>*I'm gonna swallow my tears *</i>

54
00:05:06,606 --> 00:05:10,167
You can relax, Lieutenant.
Be careful, Muntzy.
I don't know where Wilson is.

55
00:05:10,243 --> 00:05:13,076
Gray, they've burned her.
She's got a guy on her tail.

56
00:05:13,146 --> 00:05:15,808
He's in a maintenance suit.
Now stop him.

57
00:05:19,952 --> 00:05:21,681
I got her.

58
00:05:28,061 --> 00:05:30,655
And I got him.

59
00:05:34,901 --> 00:05:37,335
Excuse me.
Wait here, Mr. Acton.
And don't leave.

60
00:05:37,403 --> 00:05:39,530
What are you talking about?
Where are you going?

61
00:05:39,605 --> 00:05:41,539
Michael.
I think he made you. Muntzy.

62
00:05:41,607 --> 00:05:43,598
Muntzy.
[Acton]
Wait a minute.

63
00:05:48,047 --> 00:05:50,242
Michael, what are you doing?

64
00:06:03,963 --> 00:06:05,954
[Engine Starts]

65
00:06:10,036 --> 00:06:12,561
Muntzy!

66
00:06:16,342 --> 00:06:18,902
Watch him. I'll get help.
No, look, Lieutenant.
Forget it.

67
00:06:18,978 --> 00:06:21,139
Uh... Uh<i>- u</i>h.
<i>Muntzy.</i>

68
00:06:21,214 --> 00:06:23,739
- Go after her.
- Muntzy, you gotta hang on.

69
00:06:23,816 --> 00:06:25,875
<i>Muntzy.!</i>

70
00:06:27,053 --> 00:06:28,918
Stay here with him.

71
00:06:28,988 --> 00:06:31,218
No, I'll go with you.

72
00:06:43,302 --> 00:06:45,327
[Chattering]
[Man]
Get an ambulance.

73
00:06:45,405 --> 00:06:47,839
[Woman]
Call for a doctor someone!

74
00:06:47,907 --> 00:06:51,274
Michael, why are you doing this?
You were hired to protect Charles.

75
00:06:51,344 --> 00:06:54,472
You can't leave him.
These people are no longer
interested in your boss.

76
00:06:54,547 --> 00:06:57,311
They just got
what they were after.
What are you talking about?

77
00:06:57,383 --> 00:06:59,817
I don't have time
to explain it all to you now, Tanya,

78
00:06:59,886 --> 00:07:04,823
but your boss's chief of security
is up to his Bahamian bank accounts
in industrial espionage.

79
00:07:04,891 --> 00:07:07,189
And now murder.
I don't believe it.

80
00:07:07,260 --> 00:07:09,820
Did you believe
that dead cop back there?
He was my partner.

81
00:07:09,896 --> 00:07:11,955
I was supposed to be
covering him.

82
00:07:29,882 --> 00:07:33,374
Will you step out
of the car please, Lonnie?

83
00:07:34,454 --> 00:07:36,854
<i>You did a really nicejob.</i>

84
00:07:36,923 --> 00:07:38,823
I'll take that microfilm.

85
00:07:38,891 --> 00:07:42,122
<i>[Vehicle Approaching,</i>
<i>Tires Screech]</i>

86
00:07:44,363 --> 00:07:46,297
All right. Hold it right there.

87
00:07:46,365 --> 00:07:48,492
You move, I fire.

88
00:07:48,568 --> 00:07:51,560
<i>Drop the gun, Symes,</i>
<i>and kick it over here.</i>

89
00:07:52,738 --> 00:07:54,706
Looks like we made a small mistake.

90
00:07:54,774 --> 00:07:57,299
I'd call treason
more than a small mistake.

91
00:07:57,376 --> 00:07:59,401
<i>It draws the death penalty.</i>

92
00:07:59,479 --> 00:08:02,380
Tanya, pick up his gun.
<i>[Tanya]</i>
<i>That won't be necessary.</i>

93
00:08:04,217 --> 00:08:06,242
I have my own.
Drop it.

94
00:08:08,454 --> 00:08:09,751
<i>[Gun Clatters On Ground]</i>

95
00:08:13,559 --> 00:08:17,188
- You're workin' for them?
- Oh, I've disappointed you.

96
00:08:17,263 --> 00:08:21,597
Tanya, give me the gun.
I can still make a deal for you
if you cooperate.

97
00:08:22,602 --> 00:08:26,094
- Give it to me.
- I intend to.

98
00:08:58,671 --> 00:09:01,936
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>My God, we're too late.</i>

99
00:09:31,003 --> 00:09:33,494
[Beeping]

100
00:09:51,857 --> 00:09:54,087
Well,

101
00:09:54,160 --> 00:09:56,094
what's the word?

102
00:09:57,096 --> 00:10:01,192
I'm gonna give you the same answer
that I've been giving you
for the past four days.

103
00:10:01,267 --> 00:10:04,862
He's probably the only human being
on this planet...

104
00:10:05,871 --> 00:10:07,805
who's in worse condition than you are.

105
00:10:09,542 --> 00:10:11,533
Is he going to die?

106
00:10:11,611 --> 00:10:16,708
He should have.
That bullet was fired point-blank
right into his skull.

107
00:10:16,782 --> 00:10:18,716
<i>Well, how did he survive?</i>

108
00:10:18,784 --> 00:10:22,618
The man has a metal plate
in his forehead.

109
00:10:22,688 --> 00:10:26,784
You see?
Probably military surgery,
I would guess.

110
00:10:26,859 --> 00:10:30,886
It deflected the bullet,
which was heading
right toward his brain,

111
00:10:30,963 --> 00:10:34,694
<i>and it came back out...</i>
<i>through his face.</i>

112
00:10:35,701 --> 00:10:37,794
We'll never know what he looked like.

113
00:10:43,643 --> 00:10:45,577
[Murmurs]

114
00:10:52,551 --> 00:10:54,018
<i>Muntzy.!</i>

115
00:11:00,226 --> 00:11:02,660
<i>[Yelling]</i>
That's all right, son.

116
00:11:02,728 --> 00:11:06,755
<i>Keep hurting.</i>
<i>It'll keep you living... just like me.</i>

117
00:11:27,386 --> 00:11:30,287
I've got good news for you.
The Knight 2000 will be ready...

118
00:11:30,356 --> 00:11:32,347
Shh, shh, shh.

119
00:12:14,834 --> 00:12:18,361
- That bad?
- On the contrary.

120
00:12:18,437 --> 00:12:20,428
It's an excellent job.

121
00:12:22,408 --> 00:12:25,844
Here. Why don't you take a look?

122
00:12:32,852 --> 00:12:34,843
It isn't me.

123
00:12:34,920 --> 00:12:37,855
It gives you
a second chance to live.

124
00:12:37,923 --> 00:12:42,360
Unless, of course,
you'd prefer to walk around with a face
that might get you killed all over again?

125
00:12:42,428 --> 00:12:45,864
You take my word.
You'll be much safer with this face.

126
00:12:45,931 --> 00:12:48,491
And it's, um,

127
00:12:48,567 --> 00:12:50,364
<i>rather handsome,</i>

128
00:12:50,436 --> 00:12:52,427
if I do say so myself.

129
00:13:02,648 --> 00:13:05,242
<i>Does it strike you</i>
<i>that there's an uncanny resemblance...</i>

130
00:13:05,317 --> 00:13:08,548
between this young fellow
and you as a young man?

131
00:13:10,956 --> 00:13:13,220
[Clears Throat]

132
00:13:13,292 --> 00:13:15,283
My imagination, I suppose.

133
00:13:15,361 --> 00:13:17,352
Stick to your task.

134
00:13:17,429 --> 00:13:20,364
- When will I see it?
<i>- I've been trying to tell you.</i>

135
00:13:20,432 --> 00:13:24,027
- It could be ready within the month.
- Excellent.

136
00:13:25,604 --> 00:13:29,472
I pray that it leaves me enough time.

137
00:13:36,715 --> 00:13:41,379
<i>- What have you told him?</i>
- I've told him he no longer
has anyone to fear.

138
00:13:41,453 --> 00:13:44,479
<i>In the eyes of the law,</i>
<i>Michael Long is legally dead,</i>

139
00:13:44,557 --> 00:13:46,582
and we haven't done
anything wrong.

140
00:13:46,659 --> 00:13:50,288
Wilton, stealing a body
from the medical school...

141
00:13:50,362 --> 00:13:52,557
so that the police can find it...

142
00:13:52,631 --> 00:13:55,429
is hardly what I would call
playing by the rules.

143
00:13:55,501 --> 00:13:57,492
I make my own rules.

144
00:13:57,570 --> 00:14:00,539
So does the government.
They fake deaths
and identities all the time.

145
00:14:00,606 --> 00:14:02,369
Not to mention our adversary.

146
00:14:02,441 --> 00:14:04,568
<i>All right.</i>
<i>But why are you doing it?</i>

147
00:14:05,811 --> 00:14:07,836
I think you know why, Devon.

148
00:14:07,913 --> 00:14:10,780
I want to leave something behind me...
something worthwhile.

149
00:14:10,850 --> 00:14:13,580
Not just a lot of numbers
in a bank account.

150
00:14:14,720 --> 00:14:17,484
Now, when will the Knight 2000 be ready?

151
00:14:17,556 --> 00:14:20,354
Soon. I have the crews working
double shifts.

152
00:14:20,426 --> 00:14:24,726
Make it around the clock.
I want it done.
I want it done within the next 48 hours.

153
00:14:24,797 --> 00:14:26,731
Forty-eight hours?

154
00:14:26,799 --> 00:14:29,029
Wilton, has the doctor said...

155
00:14:29,101 --> 00:14:32,332
Don't you worry about
what the good doctor has told me.

156
00:14:32,404 --> 00:14:34,736
I'll worry about the doctors...

157
00:14:36,075 --> 00:14:38,509
and Michael Long.

158
00:14:43,215 --> 00:14:46,480
Aren't you pushing it
a bit, Michael?
[Grunts, Panting]

159
00:14:46,552 --> 00:14:49,453
I gotta get back in shape real fast.
[Panting]

160
00:14:49,521 --> 00:14:51,614
I got one last debt to pay.

161
00:14:51,690 --> 00:14:54,318
Is revenge the only thing you can think of?

162
00:14:54,393 --> 00:14:56,793
<i>You're better than that.</i>

163
00:14:56,862 --> 00:14:59,524
<i>You were a good cop.</i>

164
00:14:59,598 --> 00:15:01,589
Was I?

165
00:15:02,868 --> 00:15:04,836
As I recall, I blew it.

166
00:15:04,904 --> 00:15:07,737
What if I were to offer you another shot?

167
00:15:07,806 --> 00:15:10,866
<i>I want Tanya and her friends too,</i>

168
00:15:10,943 --> 00:15:12,934
<i>but that's only the tip of the iceberg.</i>

169
00:15:13,012 --> 00:15:17,073
- Now, if we were to work together...
- Mr. Knight, my last partner is dead.

170
00:15:18,250 --> 00:15:20,480
Nothing personal,
but from now on I work alone.

171
00:15:20,552 --> 00:15:23,715
I can't take responsibility
for anybody's life but my own.

172
00:15:24,790 --> 00:15:26,781
I think you can understand that.

173
00:15:52,751 --> 00:15:54,742
<i>[Footsteps Descending Staircase]</i>

174
00:16:09,735 --> 00:16:12,169
[Whirring]

175
00:16:24,550 --> 00:16:26,848
[Engine Starts]

176
00:16:30,756 --> 00:16:32,690
[Tires Squealing]

177
00:16:35,661 --> 00:16:38,095
Enough, Devon.

178
00:16:38,163 --> 00:16:41,394
<i>You've had your fun with our guest.</i>

179
00:16:47,072 --> 00:16:49,438
It isn't polite
to sneak around uninvited.

180
00:16:49,508 --> 00:16:51,442
[Chuckles]

181
00:16:51,510 --> 00:16:54,070
Be gracious, Devon.

182
00:16:54,146 --> 00:16:57,206
I think an explanation
is well overdue.

183
00:16:57,282 --> 00:17:01,013
Damn right it is.
What is all this?

184
00:17:01,086 --> 00:17:05,079
What are you guys up to...
people sneaking in and out of here
at all hours of the day and night?

185
00:17:05,157 --> 00:17:08,558
Look at who's talking.
Oh, be quiet, both of you.

186
00:17:08,627 --> 00:17:10,891
And let's get down to business.

187
00:17:12,431 --> 00:17:14,456
I'm running out of time,

188
00:17:14,533 --> 00:17:16,865
<i>and Michael here is...</i>

189
00:17:16,935 --> 00:17:19,768
now healthy enough to carry on.

190
00:17:19,838 --> 00:17:21,999
Carry on what?

191
00:17:22,074 --> 00:17:26,067
I don't know what
you people do out here,
but I just want to get on with my life.

192
00:17:26,145 --> 00:17:27,772
That's not very grateful.

193
00:17:27,846 --> 00:17:31,043
<i>Aren't you the least bit angry</i>
<i>at the people who le</i>ft <i>you to die?</i>

194
00:17:31,116 --> 00:17:33,050
Angry?

195
00:17:33,118 --> 00:17:35,052
Angry doesn't even come close.

196
00:17:35,120 --> 00:17:37,918
<i>But I'm gonna adjust.</i>
<i>You know why?</i>
Tell me.

197
00:17:37,990 --> 00:17:40,254
Because they're too big.

198
00:17:40,325 --> 00:17:43,624
The kind of criminals
that operate above the law.
Nobody can touch 'em.

199
00:17:43,695 --> 00:17:45,754
I don't agree with you.

200
00:17:46,999 --> 00:17:48,990
Well, you're entitled to your opinion.

201
00:17:49,068 --> 00:17:52,333
<i>As for me, I'm pulling out</i>
<i>ofhere tonight, and I, uh...</i>

202
00:17:52,404 --> 00:17:54,133
I'm taking my car with me.

203
00:17:57,076 --> 00:17:59,101
Prepare the car for him, Devon.

204
00:17:59,178 --> 00:18:03,774
<i>A great deal he'll have to know about it</i>
<i>before it's safe for him to drive.</i>

205
00:18:05,551 --> 00:18:07,246
<i>I must go to bed.</i>

206
00:18:07,319 --> 00:18:10,982
I'm not, uh...
[Chuckles]

207
00:18:11,056 --> 00:18:13,047
Feeling very well.

208
00:18:16,028 --> 00:18:18,622
You've just struck a dying man.

209
00:18:18,697 --> 00:18:21,461
Hey, listen.
I like that old man.

210
00:18:21,533 --> 00:18:25,025
I really do.
But, Devon, I gotta get on
with my own life.

211
00:18:25,104 --> 00:18:27,436
You wouldn't have a life
if we hadn't brought you here.

212
00:18:27,506 --> 00:18:31,169
<i>Remember,</i>
<i>there are still people who will kill you</i>
<i>if they find out you're alive.</i>

213
00:18:31,243 --> 00:18:33,507
But I'm legally dead, remember?

214
00:18:33,579 --> 00:18:35,638
Devon, I don't even know me
with this face.

215
00:18:35,714 --> 00:18:37,682
Now what's all this about my car?

216
00:18:37,749 --> 00:18:42,516
Any resemblance between that car
and your own is purely superficial.

217
00:18:42,588 --> 00:18:46,752
What are you talking about?
Devon, that's my car.
I left it out in the desert.

218
00:18:46,825 --> 00:18:49,385
No, it may look like your car,

219
00:18:49,461 --> 00:18:54,023
but in actuality,
this vehicle is probably
the most expensive car in the world.

220
00:18:54,099 --> 00:18:56,863
Come on. This is my car.

221
00:18:56,935 --> 00:18:59,563
What's this? A new paint job?

222
00:18:59,638 --> 00:19:02,368
It feels like baby skin.

223
00:19:02,441 --> 00:19:05,672
Boy, those guys did a nice job.
There's not a ripple on it.

224
00:19:05,744 --> 00:19:08,042
<i>Like a mirror.</i>

225
00:19:08,113 --> 00:19:10,081
It's not paint.

226
00:19:10,149 --> 00:19:14,108
It's a finish bonded
into the molecular structure
of a new substance.

227
00:19:14,186 --> 00:19:16,154
You mean the metal?

228
00:19:16,221 --> 00:19:19,213
It's not metal, and it's not fiberglass.

229
00:19:19,291 --> 00:19:21,350
Excuse me.

230
00:19:26,298 --> 00:19:29,859
<i>Here. Strike the surface</i>
<i>as hard as you can.</i>

231
00:19:29,935 --> 00:19:33,200
Come on, Devon. I'm not gonna
hit my car. It's beautiful.
Hmm.

232
00:19:36,408 --> 00:19:38,376
There's not a mark on it.

233
00:19:38,443 --> 00:19:40,434
How did you do that?

234
00:19:40,512 --> 00:19:42,707
Don't just stand there
with your mouth open.

235
00:19:42,781 --> 00:19:45,341
Get in the car.
I'll show you.

236
00:19:56,094 --> 00:19:58,187
Welcome aboard the Knight 2000.

237
00:19:58,263 --> 00:20:00,823
Thank you.
What's all this?

238
00:20:00,899 --> 00:20:03,231
Looks like Darth Vader's bathroom.

239
00:20:03,302 --> 00:20:05,930
It is a one-of-a-kind car, Mr. Long.

240
00:20:06,004 --> 00:20:09,201
It is the fastest, safest,
strongest car in the world.

241
00:20:09,274 --> 00:20:11,674
<i>It is also completely fuel-efficient...</i>

242
00:20:11,743 --> 00:20:15,042
<i>and is operated entirely</i>
<i>by microprocessors...</i>

243
00:20:15,113 --> 00:20:19,482
<i>which make it virtually impossible</i>
<i>for it to be involved in any kind of</i>
<i>mishap or collision.</i>

244
00:20:19,551 --> 00:20:23,749
Unless, of course,
specifically so ordered by its pilot.

245
00:20:23,822 --> 00:20:25,790
Pilot?

246
00:20:25,857 --> 00:20:28,553
Don't tell me this thing flies.

247
00:20:28,627 --> 00:20:31,289
No. But it thinks.

248
00:20:32,297 --> 00:20:34,424
<i>It thinks?</i>

249
00:20:34,499 --> 00:20:37,332
My car thinks?

250
00:20:37,402 --> 00:20:39,870
We like to think of it as our car.

251
00:20:40,872 --> 00:20:43,170
Now, in order to
motivate it forward...

252
00:20:43,242 --> 00:20:48,111
I recognize
the more rudimentary controls,
such as the accelerator, Devon.

253
00:20:49,114 --> 00:20:51,139
I do know how to drive.

254
00:20:58,056 --> 00:21:02,493
I would have preferred you
to have let me open the door first.

255
00:21:02,561 --> 00:21:05,223
However, as you see,
no harm has come to the car.

256
00:21:05,297 --> 00:21:07,595
You also told me this machine
couldn't have a collision.

257
00:21:07,666 --> 00:21:09,463
Not if the system is operable.

258
00:21:09,534 --> 00:21:12,628
And to do that, you have to, uh,
switch it on first.

259
00:21:12,704 --> 00:21:14,501
[Beeping]

260
00:21:14,573 --> 00:21:18,236
- Like that.
- Now you're telling me...

261
00:21:18,310 --> 00:21:21,211
I can't hit anything?

262
00:21:21,280 --> 00:21:22,941
Trust me.

263
00:21:23,015 --> 00:21:25,848
I'll never trust anybody again.

264
00:21:38,930 --> 00:21:41,296
I'm warning you, Devon.

265
00:21:41,366 --> 00:21:43,334
I'm gonna put this thing
to the test.

266
00:21:43,402 --> 00:21:45,393
Be my guest.

267
00:21:47,039 --> 00:21:48,904
[Engine Revving]

268
00:21:56,481 --> 00:21:58,813
<i>[Michael]</i>
<i>I don't believe this.</i>

269
00:21:58,884 --> 00:22:01,352
I'm playing chicken
with a 10-ton semi.

270
00:22:01,420 --> 00:22:03,081
[Beeps]

271
