Devon, the car just
drove around the truck.
It steered itself!

272
00:22:13,165 --> 00:22:15,429
Yes. It's marvelous, isn't it?
I hate it!

273
00:22:15,500 --> 00:22:17,491
I like to make my own decisions.

274
00:22:17,569 --> 00:22:21,596
Well, the microprocessor deduced
that you were acting contrary
to your best interests.

275
00:22:21,673 --> 00:22:25,234
<i>It had two choices.</i>
<i>Either to slow down...</i>

276
00:22:25,310 --> 00:22:27,403
or to maneuver around the obstacle.

277
00:22:27,479 --> 00:22:31,279
Why didn't this thing slow down
instead of driving around?
It would have been a lot safer.

278
00:22:31,350 --> 00:22:35,912
- Well, um...
- Well, why? Did I find a flaw
in your perfect machine here?

279
00:22:35,987 --> 00:22:38,080
No, no. No flaw. I assure you.

280
00:22:38,156 --> 00:22:40,090
It's just that, um...
It's just what?

281
00:22:40,158 --> 00:22:43,184
Well, it was showing off for you.

282
00:22:43,261 --> 00:22:45,752
- What?
- [Chuckles]

283
00:22:46,698 --> 00:22:48,757
<i>[Tires Screeching]</i>

284
00:22:51,103 --> 00:22:54,038
<i>Come on. You're telling me</i>
<i>that this car can just take off...</i>

285
00:22:54,106 --> 00:22:56,904
and go for gas or a car wash
just like that, huh?

286
00:22:56,975 --> 00:22:58,272
Mm-hmm.

287
00:22:58,343 --> 00:23:01,642
Well, that would be terrific
if I happened to be working under it.

288
00:23:01,713 --> 00:23:03,806
It wouldn't harm you.
I assure you.

289
00:23:03,882 --> 00:23:07,648
Its primary function is
the preservation of human life...
your life.

290
00:23:07,719 --> 00:23:10,381
By me you mean...
anybody driving this thing.

291
00:23:10,455 --> 00:23:12,616
<i>No, no, no. I mean you speci</i>f<i>ically.</i>

292
00:23:12,691 --> 00:23:14,625
You, Michael Arthur Long.

293
00:23:20,031 --> 00:23:22,022
You'd better hurry.

294
00:23:29,741 --> 00:23:32,437
<i>[Door Closes]</i>
We're too late.

295
00:23:40,018 --> 00:23:42,009
Almost.

296
00:23:44,055 --> 00:23:46,956
What kept you?
Car not fast enough?

297
00:23:47,025 --> 00:23:49,687
[Chuckles]
Look, you gotta
put that thing on the market.

298
00:23:49,761 --> 00:23:51,524
It could save
thousands of lives.

299
00:23:51,596 --> 00:23:55,862
Have it taken away from me
and kept off the market
like they did my air... airplane?

300
00:23:55,934 --> 00:23:59,461
Don't try to talk.
I'll explain everything.

301
00:24:00,572 --> 00:24:02,802
Mr. Knight is the last of his breed.

302
00:24:02,874 --> 00:24:05,809
He built his own empire
just as the Fords and the Rockefellers did.

303
00:24:05,877 --> 00:24:07,811
Devon, we've been all through this.

304
00:24:07,879 --> 00:24:11,679
All right.
Michael, come closer.

305
00:24:16,721 --> 00:24:20,487
You were spared to lead a great fight.

306
00:24:21,993 --> 00:24:24,689
<i>Don't turn away in fear.</i>

307
00:24:24,763 --> 00:24:28,096
One man <i>can...</i>

308
00:24:28,166 --> 00:24:30,157
make a difference.

309
00:24:32,103 --> 00:24:35,869
<i>And you are going to be that man.</i>

310
00:24:40,312 --> 00:24:42,303
Mr. Knight, uh,

311
00:24:43,782 --> 00:24:46,774
I'd like to be able to promise you...

312
00:24:46,852 --> 00:24:50,788
that I feel like I could
take on the world someday,
but I can't.

313
00:24:50,856 --> 00:24:53,552
I still wake up in the middle
of the night shaking.

314
00:24:54,059 --> 00:24:56,084
<i>[Gunshot Echoing]</i>

315
00:24:56,161 --> 00:25:00,063
<i>That... That gun in my face</i>
<i>and the whole world blowing up.</i>

316
00:25:01,833 --> 00:25:04,495
Remember that moment.

317
00:25:04,569 --> 00:25:09,404
Think of it as your... baptism by fire.

318
00:25:19,951 --> 00:25:24,911
My... adventure has ended.

319
00:25:26,658 --> 00:25:30,094
Yours has just...

320
00:25:32,497 --> 00:25:34,488
just begun.

321
00:25:59,324 --> 00:26:01,588
For God's sake,
don't go quite so fast.

322
00:26:01,660 --> 00:26:04,823
I'm puffed.
Sorry, Devon,
but I got places to go.

323
00:26:04,896 --> 00:26:06,989
What the hell does that mean?

324
00:26:07,065 --> 00:26:10,626
Heard you on the phone this morning.
You found the girl in California.

325
00:26:10,702 --> 00:26:14,035
What? You mean to say
that you deliberately listened in
on a private conversation?

326
00:26:14,105 --> 00:26:16,198
Listen, I don't do things like that,

327
00:26:16,274 --> 00:26:18,708
but you got so excited,
you were talking
a mile a minute.

328
00:26:18,777 --> 00:26:20,972
The gardener could have
heard you over the lawn mower.

329
00:26:21,046 --> 00:26:22,980
Now, what's she up to?

330
00:26:24,683 --> 00:26:27,151
She's working
in a place called Silicon Valley.

331
00:26:27,218 --> 00:26:30,585
All right. LfTanya's in Silicon Valley,
that's where I'm going right now.

332
00:26:30,655 --> 00:26:33,852
- I forbid it.
- Devon, you can't forbid it.

333
00:26:33,925 --> 00:26:35,893
I can certainly take away the car.

334
00:26:35,961 --> 00:26:39,021
I'll get another one.
Besides, it's in my name.

335
00:26:39,097 --> 00:26:41,088
That's where you're wrong.

336
00:26:46,371 --> 00:26:48,703
"Michael Knight"?

337
00:26:48,773 --> 00:26:50,798
Michael Long is dead.
Remember that.

338
00:26:50,875 --> 00:26:52,843
How do I suddenly become
Michael Knight?

339
00:26:52,911 --> 00:26:54,902
Yes, well...

340
00:26:57,916 --> 00:27:00,680
Driver's license,
credit cards.

341
00:27:00,752 --> 00:27:03,243
It's all on Mr. Knight's orders.

342
00:27:04,322 --> 00:27:09,123
These are good now.
You could have dated these ahead
if you wanted me to stay here.

343
00:27:09,194 --> 00:27:11,219
You knew I'd leave
when I wanted to.

344
00:27:11,296 --> 00:27:14,493
You're a primitive, Mr. Lon...
Mr. Knight.

345
00:27:14,566 --> 00:27:16,397
You're quite predictable.

346
00:27:16,468 --> 00:27:20,165
- You think the old man
was pretty smart, don't you?
- A certifiable genius.

347
00:27:20,238 --> 00:27:23,867
He must've known
what he was doing when he picked me
to get a little revenge for him.

348
00:27:25,110 --> 00:27:27,305
I'm on my way.

349
00:27:29,848 --> 00:27:33,750
Oh, just a minute.
There are several things
about this car that I ought to explain.

350
00:27:33,818 --> 00:27:36,981
That's all right. I'm a fast study.
I'll pick things up as I go along.

351
00:27:37,055 --> 00:27:39,853
<i>[Engine Starts]</i>
Look. Th-That's very foolhardy.

352
00:27:39,924 --> 00:27:43,485
Good-bye. Thank you.

353
00:27:43,561 --> 00:27:45,756
<i>Oh, and I want you to know something.</i>

354
00:27:45,830 --> 00:27:49,596
- I kind of got to like you.
- What?

355
00:27:49,668 --> 00:27:53,729
Never mind.
What's that mean coming from
a primitive anyway?

356
00:27:53,805 --> 00:27:55,796
[Tires Squealing]

357
00:28:01,413 --> 00:28:03,540
Well, Wilton,

358
00:28:03,615 --> 00:28:05,879
he's doing everything
you said he would.

359
00:28:05,950 --> 00:28:08,111
What have you gotten me into?

360
00:28:41,386 --> 00:28:44,753
<i>[Michael]</i>
<i>Millston, in Silicon Valley.</i>
<i>110 miles.</i>

361
00:28:47,459 --> 00:28:50,724
All right.
Might as well put on some music.

362
00:28:50,795 --> 00:28:53,992
With all these weird gadgets,
you'd think they'd give you a radio.

363
00:28:54,065 --> 00:28:57,501
- [Computerized Male Voice]
What would you like to hear?
- What the hell was that?

364
00:29:02,173 --> 00:29:04,733
Do you wish further information
on Silicon Valley?

365
00:29:04,809 --> 00:29:09,303
Hell, no. I want to know who you are
and how you're listening in.
There's no reason for increased volume.

366
00:29:09,380 --> 00:29:12,247
I am scanning your interrogatives
quite satisfactorily.

367
00:29:12,317 --> 00:29:16,777
I'm the voice of
Knight Industry Two Thousand's
microprocessor.

368
00:29:16,855 --> 00:29:19,187
K.I.T.T. For easy reference.

369
00:29:19,257 --> 00:29:21,191
KITT, if you prefer.

370
00:29:21,259 --> 00:29:26,788
No, I don't prefer, and what's more,
I don't intend to drive around
in a car that talks back to me.

371
00:29:26,865 --> 00:29:31,325
So, either Devon pulls your plug,
or you get yourself another driver.

372
00:29:31,402 --> 00:29:34,166
I am not qualified
to overrule your wishes.

373
00:29:34,239 --> 00:29:36,400
Well, that's real good to hear, <i>KITT,</i>

374
00:29:36,474 --> 00:29:40,706
because I don't want to hear
another peep out of you
until I can get a call off to Devon.

375
00:29:40,779 --> 00:29:42,974
So clam up.
I'm gonna listen to some good music.

376
00:29:43,047 --> 00:29:46,949
And don't offer any suggestions.
I'll choose my own.

377
00:29:47,018 --> 00:29:48,952
As you wish, Mr. Knight.

378
00:29:49,020 --> 00:29:52,012
But since you are still recovering
from your ordeal,

379
00:29:52,090 --> 00:29:54,718
and I detect are in
a slightly irritable mood
caused by fatigue,

380
00:29:54,793 --> 00:29:57,887
may I suggest you put the car
in the auto cruise mode
for safety's sake?

381
00:29:57,962 --> 00:30:00,863
No, you may not.
And that's final.

382
00:30:00,932 --> 00:30:03,492
- Good night.
- Good night.

383
00:30:03,568 --> 00:30:06,594
I can't believe this.

384
00:30:06,671 --> 00:30:08,696
A car that talks back to me.

